Narrative:
On February [XXX], 2025 at 12:10 PM PT two Waymo Autonomous Vehicles (Waymo AVs) operating in San Francisco, CA were involved in a collision involving a cyclist on [XXX].
The first Waymo AV was parked at the northwest-bound curb on [XXX] for passenger dropoff. A second Waymo AV (2024 Jaguar I-PACE SADHW2S17R1[XXX], 38,609 miles) was also parked for a separate passenger dropoff, located adjacent to the first Waymo AV with the bicycle lane of northwest-bound [XXX] between the two Waymo AVs. A bicyclist was traveling northwest-bound on [XXX] and approaching the two Waymo AVs from the rear. As the cyclist was passing between the two Waymo AVs, the rear driver side passenger of the first Waymo AV opened the door of the first Waymo AV into the cyclist. The cyclist then fell into the passenger side of the second Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, both Waymo AVs' Level 4 ADS were engaged in autonomous mode. Neither Waymo AV sustained damage. The cyclist was able to move out of the roadway independently and was then transported from the scene in an ambulance. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because an individual involved was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Other than confirmation that law enforcement is not investigating this incident, the content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted on December 6, 2024 [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]. 
On December [XXX], 2024 at 10:54 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a plastic crate on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound in the center lane on [XXX], crossing the intersection with [XXX] when the front passenger side of the Waymo AV made contact with a plastic crate that was in the roadway within the Waymo AV's lane of travel. The contact with the Waymo AV caused the crate to move into the adjacent right lane, which was occupied by a scooterist. The front tire of the scooter made contact with the crate and the scooter and scooterist fell. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Given the speed at which the scooter was traveling at the time of the contact, the scooter may have sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Cruise submits this updated report to confirm there was no physical contact between the AV and the cyclist and to provide additional details about this incident. On November [XXX], 2024 at 7:23PM CST, a Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV") operating in supervised autonomous mode in Houston, Texas was traveling west on [XXX] when it decelerated as it approached a speed bump. As the AV began to slowly traverse the speed bump, it maneuvered slightly left to provide room for a cyclist approaching from behind the AV on the right-hand side. As the cyclist approached quickly from behind the AV, they moved from the right side of the road to the left side and attempted to maneuver around the AV, between the AV and a parked vehicle. The cyclist then lost control of their bike while maneuvering the speed bump and fell to the ground in front of and to the left of the AV. The AV came to a complete stop and the Cruise safety driver took manual control of the AV, remaining stationary. The cyclist proceeded to get to their feet and spoke with the safety driver, but did not report any injuries when asked. There was no indication of property damage to the AV.

Narrative:
**1-Day Incident Report 5/25/2024**
Customer contacted Kia Customer Care (KCC) to report an incident involving his 2023MY Kia Sportage. Specifically, the customer called to thank Kia "for saving [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] life." Customer explained he was in a head-on collision when a drunk driver suddenly veered into his lane.  Customer reported he suffered "cuts, bumps & bruises" and stated he "believes that [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] lack of injuries is due to the plethora of safety features my Sportage had."  KCC subsequently contacted the customer to obtain additional details regarding the incident.  Customer stated that he was driving on a two-lane highway around 3AM, with cruise control engaged, when the car he was following veered into a ditch and a drunk driver veered into his lane. Customer did not see the drunk driver until the last second and as a result did not have time react.  When asked by KCC, the customer responded that Highway Driving Assist (HDA) was not engaged, but that his Smart Cruise Control and Lane Following Assist were engaged at the time of the incident.  The customer reported that the Sportage's airbags deployed, both the customer and driver of the other vehicle (unclear if the drunk driver or the driver of the vehicle that veered into the ditch) were transported to the hospital and that the Sportage was towed. Customer stated he was not asking anything from Kia and that he had called only to share his appreciation. 
This incident is being reported as precautionary measure since the incident meets the requirements under the SGO.  However, based on the description of the incident provided by the customer, the incident was not caused by a failure and/or disengagement of smart cruise control and/or LFA.
**10-Day Update 6/3/2024**
No additional information to be provided as the 1-Day was reported as a precautionary measure and submitting this 10-Day Update per the reporting requirements under the SGO.

On June [XXX], 2022 at approximately 4:50 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California allegedly contributed to a collision between a passenger vehicle and a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX], according to a claim by the driver of the passenger vehicle.
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode and preparing to enter southbound [XXX] as a passenger vehicle on [XXX] approached from behind.  A pickup truck was traveling next to the passenger vehicle in the adjacent left lane.  As the passenger vehicle approached the Waymo AV from behind, the passenger vehicle entered the adjacent left lane that was occupied by the pickup truck and maneuvered around the Waymo AV.  The pickup truck proceeded without stopping, and the passenger vehicle's driver shortly after signaled to the Waymo AV test driver to pull over.  The Waymo AV test driver then transitioned to manual mode and pulled over.  Transdev has no data or knowledge of any contact between any of the three vehicles.  There was no contact or collision between the Waymo AV and any other vehicle.  However, the driver and passenger in the passenger vehicle have subsequently alleged injuries based on alleged contact between the pick-up truck and passenger vehicle, which contact their allegations attribute to the behavior of Waymo's AV in a bodily injury claim under Waymo's insurance policy.  Waymo received notice of this insurance claim on July [XXX].
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this event under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of 30270-3655-1.

According to the information provided, a 2021 Kona EV was being operated by a non-production SAE Level 4 ADAS in an unknown mode when the Level 4 system experienced a communication error, switched to an auxiliary backup system, resulting in the vehicle crashing into a road sign/ pole.  The vehicle was undrivable post-crash.  No injuries were reported.
Hyundai notes that the subject vehicle was produced and sold with SAE Level 1 and below ADAS only.  
Hyundai also notes that it has not collaborated with Pony.ai since February 2020.
